    <abstract>
      <t>
        Communication sessions in RTCWeb are described and negotiated using Session Description Protocol(SDP)[RFC4566] mechanisms. 
        SDP uses attributes to describes specific aspects of such a session. Since its inception, several attributes have been 
        introduced into SDP for the aforementioned purpose.The scope of this document is to provide generic framework for analyzing 
        SDP attributes and its applicability in solving use-cases specific to RTCWeb.
      </t>
    </abstract>
  </front>

  <middle>
    <section title="Introduction">
      <t> 
        The RTCWeb working group is responsible for defining protocol to support direct interactive multimedia sessions
        between peers. With in this framework, Session Description protocol (SDP) [RFC4566] is used for describing multi-media session
        capabilities. A multi-media session description needs to convey information such as sources, sinks and encodings 
        corresponding to the media along with transport capabilities required to carry the encoded media to the peer.
        SDP defines several attributes for describing specific aspects of a multimedia session. Given the number of SDP attributes 
        registered with IANA [IANA_REF] till date and possibility of defining new attributes in the future, there is need 
        for future-proof framework to analyze these attributes for their applicability in supporting RTCWeb use-cases.
      </t>
      <t>
        The document starts with providing the motivation for requiring such a framework within the context
        of RTCWeb. This is followed by introduction to the SDP attribute analysis framework/procedures, following which 
        several sections applies the framework to the SDP attributes registered with IANA [IANA_REF].
      </t>
    </section>
    <section title="Terminology">
      <t>The key words "MUST", "MUST NOT", "REQUIRED", "SHOULD", "SHOULD NOT",
        "RECOMMENDED", "MAY", and "OPTIONAL" in this document are to be
        interpreted as described in <xref target="RFC2119"></xref>.</t>
      </section>
    <section title="Motivation">
      <t>
        One of the major driving factors motivating the need for a framework to analyze SDP attributes is 
        media stream multiplexing requirement.This requirement attempts to reduce the number of media transports in order
        to preserve network resources such as port numbers by multiplexing multiple media streams in a given SDP
        over same underlying transport.
        This imposes further restrictions on applicability of these SDP attributes as they are defined 
        today.
       </t> 
      <t>
        As of today there are close to 180 SDP attributes registered with the IANA and more SHALL be added in the future.
        There is no clearly defined procedure to establish the validity/applicability of these attribute to the 
        use-cases defined in the RTCWeb.
      </t>
      <t>
        Lastly,RTCWeb inter-operability requirements with legacy and future VOIP systems presupposes the need for analyzing the current
        and future SDP attributes for RTCWeb - VOIP interoperability multimedia scenarios.
      </t>        
    </section>
    <section title="SDP Attribute Analysis Framework">
    <t>
     The [IANA_REF] lists the attributes registered with IANA since the inception of Session Description Protocol. Any framework or procedure
     to analyze these attributes should be able to 1) Be able to clearly explain the semantic applicability of the attribute while describing  
     RTCWeb Multimedia session and 2) SHOULD be future-proof.
    </t>
    <t> 
     An SDP session description consists of a session-level section followed by zero or more media-level sections that could be 
     broken down into following high-level categories
     <list>
       <t>Descriptions related to media sources and sinks such as media type, encoding schemes, payload types to name a few.</t>
       <t>Descriptions specifying media transport characteristics like RTP/RTCP port, network addresses, QOS and so on.</t>
       <t>Session Metadata descriptions such as session timing and origin information.</t>
       <t>Descriptions establishing relationships across media streams.</t>
     </list>
    </t>  
    <t>  
      Over the several years, several IETF Working Group documents have extended the base SDP [RFC4566] specification and thus 
      represent a semantic grouping for the attributes thus introduced. The authors believe that a framework based on grouping the SDP
      attributes per RFC to describe their applicability in the context of RTCWeb serves a better purpose.
    </t>
    <t>
       Based on the motivations established in the section [SECTION-MOTIVATION], the proposed framework attempts to seggregate the 
       attributes into one of the following categories.
       <list>
         <t>Media Source (MS) - Attributes that could be independently specified per media source.</t>
         <t>Don't Multiplex (DM) - Attributes that are recommended against session multiplexing.</t>
         <t>No Change (NC) - Attributes that carry their existing semantics. </t>
         <t>Repeat (R)  - Attributes that MUST be reported across the media lines if session multiplexing.</t>

       </list>
    </t>
    <t>
      The idea behind these categories is to provide recommendations for using the attributes in solving RTCWeb use-cases.
    </t>  
    <t>
      Following sub-sections analyzes attributes listed in [IANA_REF] grouped under the IETF document that defines them. 
      For each such section, the single-letter acronyms "S", "M" and "B" under the "Current" column specify existing semantics as
      applicable to either session-level or media-level or both respectively. 
    </t> 
    <section title="RFC4566">      
     <t>
       RFC4566 defines the Session Description Protocol (SDP) that is intended for describing multimedia sessions for the
       purposes of session announcement, session invitation, and other forms of multimedia session initiation      
     </t>
      
